{"batch":"Cross-cutting Sweep","batch_index":6,"assessments":{"naming_quality":88.4,"logic_clarity":87.6,"type_safety":90.2,"contract_coherence":79.8,"initialization_coupling":81.4,"convention_outlier":84.7,"api_surface_coherence":78.9,"authorization_consistency":91.3},"dimension_notes":{"naming_quality":{"evidence":["`StartVersionSubsystem` in `goseg/routines/version.go` delegates to a blocking runner, while other `Start*` APIs in the batch are non-blocking, so naming no longer reliably signals call behavior.","`DockerData(pathType string)` in `goseg/defaults/defaults.go` uses opaque string selectors (`\"volumes\"` vs everything else), reducing intent clarity at call sites like `goseg/config/runtimecontext/context.go`."],"impact_scope":"module","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","confidence":"high","issues_preventing_higher_score":"Naming communicates domain intent in many places, but behavior-signaling prefixes/suffixes are not consistently trustworthy across runtime/startup APIs."},"logic_clarity":{"evidence":["`runAutoVersionUpdateLoop` in `goseg/routines/version.go` suppresses first and second updater failures by design and only exits on the third; this is intentional but makes failure semantics less obvious at call sites.","`dockerSubscriptionHandlerWithRuntime` in `goseg/docker/orchestration/subsystem/subsystem_events.go` resets failure counters on unhandled actions, which can obscure whether transition workflow instability is persistent versus event-noise-driven."],"impact_scope":"module","fix_scope":"single_edit","confidence":"medium","issues_preventing_higher_score":"Control flow is mostly direct, but some resilience loops encode nuanced retry/window behavior without a single explicit policy surface."},"type_safety":{"evidence":["Typed runtime seam structs (`workflowRuntime`, `RuntimeContainerOps`, `RuntimeSnapshotOps`) enforce many compile-time contracts across orchestration and workflow modules.","`PublishTransitionWithPolicy[T any]` in `goseg/shipworkflow/operations_runtime.go` accepts a `func(T)` publisher (no error return), which weakens compile-time enforcement for delivery-failure handling compared with `events.EventBroker` methods that return `error`."],"impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","confidence":"high","issues_preventing_higher_score":"Most boundaries are typed, but one generic transition publishing seam erases failure signaling in type signatures."},"contract_coherence":{"evidence":["`events.EventBroker` publish methods return `error` (`goseg/docker/events/events.go`), but multiple callers in `goseg/shipworkflow/newship.go` ignore those errors in `HandleNewShipBoot` and `ResetNewShip`.","`emitWorkflowTransitionResolved` in `goseg/shipworkflow/operations_runtime.go` explicitly applies `transition.HandleTransitionPublishError`, showing a stricter contract than neighboring direct publish calls."],"impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","confidence":"high"},"initialization_coupling":{"evidence":["Mutable process-wide singleton runtimes exist in several modules: `defaultEventRuntime` (`goseg/docker/events/events.go`), `defaultBroadcastStateRuntime` and loop controller (`goseg/broadcast/state.go`, `goseg/broadcast/loop.go`), and `defaultDockerSubsystemRuntime` (`goseg/docker/orchestration/subsystem/subsystem_events.go`).","Public setters (`SetDefaultEventRuntime`, `SetDefaultBroadcastStateRuntime`, `SetDefaultBroadcastLoopController`) allow runtime behavior to change globally after startup, coupling behavior to initialization order and test sequencing."],"impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"architectural_change","confidence":"high"},"convention_outlier":{"evidence":["Runtime config serialization uses mixed key conventions in the same struct (`CfgDir` tagged as `json:\"CFG_DIR\"` in `goseg/structs/configs.go`, while sibling fields use camelCase tags).","Patch/update plumbing normalizes around `cfgDir`/`CfgDir` in `goseg/config/config_update_registry.go`, creating a compatibility island distinct from the persisted `CFG_DIR` shape."],"impact_scope":"module","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","confidence":"medium"},"api_surface_coherence":{"evidence":["`Start*` APIs have conflicting semantics across modules: `StartVersionSubsystem` and `StartBackupRoutinesWithContext` block (`goseg/routines/version.go`, `goseg/routines/system/system.go`), while `StartDockerSubsystemWithRuntime` is fire-and-return (`goseg/docker/orchestration/subsystem/subsystem_events.go`).","`DockerData(pathType string)` (`goseg/defaults/defaults.go`) exposes a stringly-typed selector contract where invalid values silently map to a fallback branch, making the API shape hard to use safely."],"impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","confidence":"high"},"authorization_consistency":{"evidence":["Leak broadcast path applies differentiated payload scoping by auth state (`status.Auth`) in `goseg/leak/broadcast.go`, preserving a clear authorized vs scoped-unauthorized split.","No contradictory authorization bypass pattern was observed in the sampled cross-cutting files; auth-sensitive publish pathways are mostly delegated to existing session/leak state."],"impact_scope":"module","fix_scope":"single_edit","confidence":"medium","issues_preventing_higher_score":"Authorization behavior is mostly consistent in sampled files, but several transition/event publishers bypass explicit error handling, reducing observability if auth-gated deliveries fail."}},"findings":[{"dimension":"api_surface_coherence","identifier":"start_api_semantics_diverge","summary":"`Start*` methods mix blocking and non-blocking semantics across sibling runtimes","related_files":["goseg/routines/version.go","goseg/routines/system/system.go","goseg/docker/orchestration/subsystem/subsystem_events.go"],"evidence":["`StartVersionSubsystem` delegates to `RunVersionSubsystemWithContext` and blocks until cancellation/worker failure.","`StartBackupRoutinesWithContext` starts goroutines but then blocks on `<-ctx.Done()`.","`StartDockerSubsystemWithRuntime` starts a goroutine and returns immediately, so the same `Start` prefix implies different lifecycle behavior."],"suggestion":"Standardize lifecycle API shape across subsystems: either make `Start*` consistently non-blocking with paired `Run*`/`Wait*` APIs, or rename blocking starters to `Run*` and keep `Start*` for fire-and-return only.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"runtime_boundary_contract_drift"},{"dimension":"contract_coherence","identifier":"event_publish_errors_ignored","summary":"Transition publish contract is inconsistently honored (errors handled in some paths, dropped in others)","related_files":["goseg/shipworkflow/newship.go","goseg/shipworkflow/operations_runtime.go","goseg/docker/events/events.go"],"evidence":["`EventBroker.Publish*` methods return `error`, but `HandleNewShipBoot` and `ResetNewShip` call `PublishNewShipTransition` without checking returned errors.","`emitWorkflowTransitionResolved` routes publish errors through `transition.HandleTransitionPublishError`, showing a stricter contract in adjacent workflow code.","This creates split behavior where some transition failures are policy-managed and others are silently lost."],"suggestion":"Route all event publishing through a single helper that enforces one error policy (critical/non-critical) and return/log outcomes consistently; update direct `DefaultEventRuntime().Publish*` call sites to use that helper.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"runtime_boundary_contract_drift"},{"dimension":"initialization_coupling","identifier":"mutable_global_runtime_singletons","summary":"Global mutable default runtimes create boot-order and test-order coupling","related_files":["goseg/docker/events/events.go","goseg/broadcast/state.go","goseg/broadcast/loop.go","goseg/docker/orchestration/subsystem/subsystem_events.go"],"evidence":["Each module exposes package-level default runtime state plus mutators (`SetDefault*`), allowing runtime behavior changes outside composition root.","`Start*` entrypoints often implicitly read defaults, so effective dependencies vary based on prior global mutations.","This pattern makes initialization order part of correctness and can cause cross-test leakage when defaults are replaced."],"suggestion":"Move default-runtime wiring to explicit composition at startup (main/startup orchestrator) and pass runtime instances through constructors/functions; keep package globals only as backward-compatible shims that delegate to injected instances.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"architectural_change","root_cause_cluster":"global_runtime_state_coupling"},{"dimension":"convention_outlier","identifier":"runtime_config_keyshape_drift","summary":"Runtime config uses mixed key casing conventions (`CFG_DIR` vs camelCase peers)","related_files":["goseg/structs/configs.go","goseg/config/config_update_registry.go"],"evidence":["`RuntimeConfig.CfgDir` is tagged `json:\"CFG_DIR\"` while adjacent fields use camelCase tags (e.g., `updateInterval`, `binHash`).","Update registry surfaces `cfgDir`/`CfgDir` for patching, so runtime config key conventions differ between persistence and patch APIs."],"suggestion":"Introduce a compatibility migration to canonicalize `CfgDir` to one key convention (prefer camelCase), accept legacy keys during read, and write only the canonical key to reduce long-term contract drift.","confidence":"medium","impact_scope":"module","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"runtime_boundary_contract_drift"}],"retrospective":{"root_causes":["Runtime boundary design evolved piecemeal: lifecycle semantics, publish error policy, and config key contracts are not enforced by one shared abstraction.","Package-level default runtime singletons were used for convenience/testing but now leak into production call paths, coupling behavior to global state."],"likely_symptoms":["start_api_semantics_diverge","event_publish_errors_ignored","runtime_config_keyshape_drift"],"possible_false_positives":["`CFG_DIR` may be intentionally preserved for strict backward compatibility with external tooling; if so, issue scope is convention debt rather than a hard contract bug."]}}


